  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "Caused by spirochete\nBorrelia burgdorferi\nTypically carried on Ixodes scapularis aka Deer tick\nThe spirochete\nBorrelia mayonii\nhas been a new strain implicated in cases in the midwest\n[1]\nEndemic to the northeastern US\nPeak time of infection is May to August\nStages: Early localized infection, early disseminated, and late disseminated",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Clinical_Features": {
      "text": "3 Distinct Stages - Not all patients suffer all stages, and stages may overlap with remissions between stages",
      "subsections": {
        "Early_Localized_Infection_(7-14_Days)": {
          "text": "Erythema Chronicum Migrans: Occurs at site of tick bite, beginning with red macule that expands outward. Starts 3-30 days after bite and occurs in 70-80% of cases\nErythema migrans rash more often without central clearing\nFatigue, low grade\nfever\n, migrating\narthralgia\n, lymphadenopathy,\nheadache\n, nausea/\nvomiting\n,\nabdominal pain",
          "tables": []
        },
        "Early_Disseminated_Infection_(Days_to_Weeks)": {
          "text": "Skin- Multiple annular lesions that spare the palm and soles\nNervous System-fluctuating\nmeningoencephalitis\n,\nheadache\n,\nnausea/vomiting\n,\ncranial nerve palsies\n(ie 7th-can be bilateral) peripheral neuropathy, radiculopathy\nCardiovascular:\nAV blocks\n,\nRBBB\n,\ndysrhythmias\n, LV dysfunction\nEye:\nConjunctivitis\n, keratitis,\nretinal detachment\n,\noptic neuritis",
          "tables": []
        },
        "Late_Disseminated_Infection_(Months_to_Years)": {
          "text": "Arthritis: Monarticularule outligoarticular asymmetric arthritis (large joints-commonly knee)\nBrief episodes separated with complete remission\nMigratory pattern may occur\nNervous System: Subtle encephalopathy, fatigue, polyneuropathy",
          "tables": []
        }
      },
